(3) Ushering in the Thermodynamic Future [ https://substack.com/redirect/a3=
c1dbb5-29d0-4d17-8ab4-87978f1267c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Guillaume Verdon & Trevor McCourt for Extropic
Extropic=E2=80=99s superconducting chips are entirely passive, meaning we o=
nly expend energy when measuring or manipulating its state. This likely mak=
es these neurons the most energy-efficient in the universe.
Not Boring Capital portfolio company Extropic AI came out of stealth a litt=
le earlier than expected when Forbes doxxed its co-founder [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/78c970e2-d169-4ad8-b29e-84f08079ea2f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], Beff Jezos/Guillaume Verdon=
, late last year. The company promised that it would explain more about wha=
t it was up to soon.=20
On Monday, it did, releasing a litepaper that provides some more detail on =
its plans to build thermodynamic chips. Sitting between classical computing=
 and quantum computing, thermodynamic computing essentially uses the fluctu=
ations of electrons as random number generators to provide the randomness n=
eeded for Energy-Based Models.
Energy-Based Models perform well when there=E2=80=99s limited data or when =
modeling tail events by taking a brute force-ish approach: it imagines all =
possible events, including those not in the training data, assigns probabil=
ities to each event based on their compatibility with the data, and penaliz=
e the lower-probability events. Imagining every possible event and assignin=
g probabilities to each of them would consume a ton of energy in a classica=
l computer, but by using nature=E2=80=99s randomness and baking it into the=
 physics of the chips, Extropic gets that energy practically for free and c=
an operate orders of magnitude faster.=20
These models might be very useful in applying generative AI to weather fore=
casting or financial markets, among other high-value use cases.
If you want more explanation than my feeble human brain can provide, check =
out the litepaper and:
Andrew C=C3=B4t=C3=A9=E2=80=99s tweet explainer [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/4a2fb8c2-5051-4ce4-b9d4-11bbac6b86c2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Guillaume and Trevor on Christian Keil=E2=80=99s First Principles [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/3177bd20-26c2-4fed-91df-b07382231e7b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Guillaume and Trevor in conversation with Garry Tan [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/53b9448d-6172-4167-ba27-11799d5baa9d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Extropic is taking a massive swing and attempting to accelerate the next er=
a of computing, which Guillame and Trevor believe is inevitable as silicon =
transistors hit =E2=80=9CMoore=E2=80=99s Wall.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99re bui=
lding analog chips and the software that runs on top of them. If they succe=
ed, C=C3=B4t=C3=A9 wrote that they=E2=80=99ll build the Transistor for the =
AGI Era that =E2=80=9Cunblocks fundamental progress, relaxes resource const=
raints, and forever changes the world.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a swing wort=
h taking.=20
(4) Sharing a Bit More About Reflect Orbital [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/ba393651-e4da-4444-a56f-162aa4a5aa94?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By precisely reflecting sunlight that is endlessly available in space to sp=
ecific targets on the ground, we can create a world where sunlight powers s=
olar farms for longer than just daytime, and in doing this, commoditize sun=
light.
Ben Nowack for Reflect Orbital=20
Even when Extropic makes computing much more energy efficient, we=E2=80=99r=
e still going to need to consume a ton of energy. That=E2=80=99s how we pro=
gress.=20
The curves suggest that solar is going to have an enormous role to play in =
producing that energy =E2=80=94 it just keeps getting cheaper as we build m=
ore of it.=20
One of the most interesting things happening now that people are beginning =
to trust solar=E2=80=99s curve is that there are businesses being built to =
complement and enhance solar. Batteries are the obvious complement =E2=80=
=94 they keep getting cheaper too, though not as fast as solar itself.
But there are more creative complements, too. Terraform Industries, which u=
ses solar to produce synthetic fuels, is one that I=E2=80=99ve written abou=
t a few times. And this week, a startup called Reflect Orbital [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/b751f0bf-3dab-4540-8511-87f7468a8903?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] announced what it=E2=80=
=99s been building on twitter.=20
Reflect sits at the intersection of two curves: cheaper solar and cheaper l=
aunch. It plans to send satellites with mirrors on them into orbit, and use=
 those satellites to reflect sunlight on solar farms when it=E2=80=99s dark=
=2E Nighttime has been one of solar=E2=
=80=99s biggest challenges; Reflect is=20=
kinda trying to solve night. If they do, they=E2=80=99ll make solar panels =
and solar farms more productive, make them even better investments, and dri=
ve the price down even further as they drive installations up. =20
Now if that doesn=E2=80=99t brighten up your day=E2=80=A6=20
(5) With OpenAI, Figure 01 can now have full conversations with people [ ht=
