could provide you with from the table.
=E2=80=94 A robot, while also picking up trash
Just watch the video.=20
That robot wasn=E2=80=99t coded to do any of the things in the video specif=
ically. It was trained on a lot of video data, and is now able to respond t=
o verbal requests to do physical things in real-time thanks to that trainin=
g and a partnership with OpenAI.=20
This comes weeks after Figure, the company behind the bot, announced a $675=
 million round at a $2.6 billion valuation from investors including Jeff Be=
zos, Nvidia, Microsoft, and OpenAI.=20
Like Devin, this is as dumb as these robots are ever going to be. Every tim=
e one of them learns how to do something new, all of them will know how to =
do it, like the Neo =E2=80=9CI know Kung Fu=E2=80=9D thing from the Matrix =
applied to a growing fleet of humanoid robots.=20
Energy, dexterity, and intelligence [ https://substack.com/redirect/da2634f=
1-6034-4ed0-b3e6-ae467b829ef2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=A6 it=E2=80=99s all happening.=20
(6) Ethereum Completes EIP-4844 Upgrade [ https://substack.com/redirect/402=
daa0b-26ce-40d7-94a5-209a369f036c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
One of Ethereum=E2=80=99s biggest challenges historically has been that it=
=E2=80=99s expensive to do anything on the chain. Gas fees are regularly ~$=
5-10 and can spike into the hundreds of dollars.=20
In response to that challenge, a number of groups have built Layer 2s (L2s)=
 that handle a bunch of transactions off of the Ethereum mainnet, and then =
send them down in batches. L2s have brought gas fees sub-$1. If you=E2=80=
=99re making a big trade or buying a valuable NFT, something like $0.30 is =
nothing, but if you want to bring all sorts of actions onchain, asking user=
s to pay $0.30 each time is still tough. Imagine having to fork over 30 cen=
ts every time you like a tweet.=20
In 2022, Ethereum devs drafted and implemented a proposal, EIP-4844, that i=
ntroduced =E2=80=9Cblob-carrying transactions=E2=80=9D to lower costs and i=
mprove scalability. Blob-carrying transactions contain a large amount of da=
ta, called =E2=80=9Cblobs,=E2=80=9D that can be used to bundle multiple tra=
nsactions together and process them off-chain. The blobs are stored on the =
Ethereum network for a short period, allowing anyone to download and verify=
 the data if needed. This ensures data availability for L2s.
This week, Ethereum successfully completed the Mainnet upgrade to 4844. Gas=
 fees on L2s have plummeted to less than 1 cent in most cases, a longstandi=
ng holy grail.=20
I view blockchains as platforms [ https://substack.com/redirect/38e0cc97-c4=
e5-4486-bff9-f50b4f1cedbc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and think that the more trade-offs that get eliminated=
, the more developers will build onchain to take advantage of blockchains=
=E2=80=99 unique properties. Cost has been a really big trade-off. I=E2=80=
=99m excited to see what people cook up with sub-cent transaction costs.=20
(7) Company aiming to =E2=80=98de-extinct=E2=80=99 mammoths creates elephan=
t stem cell line [ https://substack.com/redirect/52bf5170-5258-428f-b602-b9=
4013e7e383?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]
Christie Wilcox for Science
A biotech company has succeeded in converting skin cells from Asian elephan=
ts (Elephas maximus) into stem cells [ https://substack.com/redirect/8e35e9=
e8-022c-41f8-b196-1f74db9f8d9d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] capable of growing into the layered cells that bec=
ome vertebrate tissues=E2=80=94a feat that may not only help conserve the e=
ndangered species, but also aid efforts to bring long-extinct woolly mammot=
hs back to life.
=E2=80=9CYour scientists were so preoccupied with whether or not they could=
, they didn=E2=80=99t stop to think if they should.=E2=80=9D
Just getting the obvious Jurassic Park line out of the way here before lett=
ing you know that a startup co-founded by legendary Harvard geneticist Geor=
ge Church successfully converted the skin cells from Asian elephants into s=
tem cells, which can grow into other types of cells and bingo bongo, the wo=
oly mammoths are back.=20
Colossal [ https://substack.com/redirect/b77c9593-20e7-4e12-8ea6-f532daa061=
95?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], th=
e company behind the work, has a lot left before it can meet its splashy in=
itial goal of de-extincting the wooly mammoth, but its a step towards an ab=
solutely =E2=80=A6 colossal =E2=80=A6 step in its mission to make extinctio=
n extinct.=20
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday. Until then, spread the good=
 news:
Thanks for reading,
